      "content": "The movement's success was not solely due to nonviolence; it was a powerful combination of sustained grassroots pressure and shifting national politics. The growing economic and social costs of maintaining segregation, coupled with increased media scrutiny, made the status quo politically untenable for the federal government. Furthermore, the political climate of the mid-20th century, with its growing awareness of moral failings, created the necessary window for legislative action.",
